    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "```python3\r\nclass ABC:\r\n    def __init_subclass__(cls):\r\n        print(cls)\r\n\r\n\r\nclass SubClass(ABC):\r\n    pass\r\n\r\n```\r\nIf you run this with python directly, it gives:\r\n```\r\n<class '__main__.SubClass'>\r\n```\r\nBut after I compile it with cython, it gives:\r\n```\r\nTypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)\r\n<ipython-input-1-a0954f22e2a4> in <module>\r\n----> 1 import test\r\n\r\ntest.pyx in init test()\r\n\r\nTypeError: __init_subclass__() takes exactly one argument (0 given)\r\n```\r\nHow to solve it? ",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The relevant bits of [PEP-487](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0487/) need to get implemented. Specifically, `__init_subclass__()` is an implicit class method and must be treated as such, and class creation should call the `__init_subclass__()` method in older Python versions (before 3.6).\r\n\r\nI assume you were using Py3.6 or later for your tests, right?",
            "created_at": "2019-01-04T14:39:46Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/2781#issuecomment-451461356",
